## Budgets

- Target: < 100KB JS per page (excluding Next.js framework shared chunk)
- First meaningful paint: < 2s on 3G
- All pages should be statically prerenderable
- No external API calls at build time
- Lazy load heavy game components if needed
- Interaction lag: < 50ms for game moves

## How Loading Works

Next.js **code-splits** each route into its own JS chunk. Adding more games does NOT
increase the load time of any individual page:

- The hub page loads only `game-grid.tsx` + `hero-section.tsx` + game metadata (no game logic)
- Each game page loads only its own `client.tsx` and `lib/games/<slug>.ts`
- Static prerendering means pages are served as HTML + minimal JS hydration
- The shared chunk (React + Next.js runtime, ~102KB) is loaded once and cached

## Scaling to 50+ Games

- **Hub page**: Game registry metadata is tiny (~200 bytes per game). Even 100 games
  would add < 20KB to the hub bundle. The grid uses CSS auto-fill for layout.
- **Images**: Use Next.js `<Image>` with `loading="lazy"` for game icons/thumbnails.
  Keep icons as SVG (< 5KB each) or optimized PNG.
- **New game bundles**: Each new game is isolated. A complex game with heavy logic
  (e.g., chess AI) doesn't affect other games' load times.
- **Deployment**: Vercel and Cloudflare Pages handle static sites with CDN caching.
  Adding pages doesn't increase hosting costs on free tiers.
